SEGMENT 2 (5:00 - 10:00) | SPEAKER B
"Microservices Communication and ML Pipeline Deep Dive"
Estimated Words: ~650
================================================================================

[Navigate to the "Architecture Diagrams" section. Click the second diagram:
"2. Microservices Communication".]

Thank you, [Speaker A]. You have shown the complete architecture and our
technology stack. Now let me explain how these services actually communicate
with each other and how data flows through our ML pipeline.

This diagram zooms into the communication patterns. Look at the arrows.
The API Gateway communicates with all four backend services via REST API
calls. The key arrow labeled "verify token" shows that every protected
request triggers a call to the Auth Service. The green arrow from Training
Service to MLflow shows where experiment metrics are logged. The red arrows
from Prometheus show it actively scraping the /metrics endpoint from all
four Flask services every fifteen seconds. And the yellow "PromQL" arrow
shows Grafana querying Prometheus for visualization data.

Notice that Airflow connects to the Training Service with "triggers DAG."
This is how admin-initiated retraining works: the API Gateway calls the
Airflow REST API, which triggers a DAG that orchestrates the entire
retraining pipeline.

[Click anywhere to close. Click the third diagram: "3. ML Pipeline -
From Data to Prediction".]

This diagram is extremely important because it shows the journey from
raw data all the way to a live prediction. Follow it left to right.

We start with five point six gigabytes of raw data: CSV files and images.
The second step is preprocessing, where we perform tokenization and text
cleaning using NLTK. We remove HTML tags, filter out non-alphabetic
characters, remove French stopwords, and apply lemmatization. We truncate
every description to its first ten words.

Then feature engineering: we convert words to integer sequences using a
Keras tokenizer with a vocabulary of ten thousand words, and pad every
sequence to a length of ten.

The LSTM Training stage trains our neural network for ten epochs across
twenty-seven product categories. After training, model evaluation logs
loss and accuracy metrics to MLflow. The trained model is then registered
in the MLflow Model Registry for versioning. And finally, the Prediction
API serves classifications in real time.

Notice the three colored bars at the bottom: DVC covers the reproducible
data pipeline, MLflow covers experiment tracking from training through
deployment, and Airflow orchestrates the entire end-to-end workflow.

Now [Speaker A] will show you the live features in action.


