SEGMENT 3 (10:00 - 15:00) | SPEAKER A
"Live Demonstrations: Prediction, Retraining, and Monitoring"
Estimated Words: ~680
================================================================================

[Navigate to the "Predict" tab by clicking "Predict" in the top navigation.]

Thank you, [Speaker B]. Now let me show you the system doing what it was
built to do: classifying products. This is the Predict panel.

[Click into the textarea and type: "Samsung Galaxy smartphone 128GB,
dual camera, fast charging"]

I am entering a product description: "Samsung Galaxy smartphone 128GB,
dual camera, fast charging."

[Click the "Classify" button. Wait for the result to appear.]

And there it is. The system classified this as a clothing category with
a confidence score shown in the green bar below. Let me explain what
happened behind the scenes in that one click.

The dashboard sent a POST request with my text and my Bearer token to
the API Gateway. The Gateway first verified my token by calling the Auth
Service. After validation, it forwarded my text to the Prediction Service.
Inside the Prediction Service, the text went through the exact same
preprocessing pipeline [Speaker B] described: HTML removal, regex cleaning,
French stopword removal, lemmatization, and truncation to ten words. Then
the Keras tokenizer converted those words to integer sequences, padded
them to length ten, and fed them into our LSTM model. The model has an
Embedding layer with one hundred twenty-eight dimensions, an LSTM layer
with one hundred twenty-eight units, and a Dense output layer with
twenty-seven neurons using softmax activation. It returned a probability
distribution across all twenty-seven categories, and the highest
probability became our prediction.

[Navigate to the "History" tab by clicking "History" in the navigation.]

Every prediction is automatically saved. This history panel shows the
text, the predicted category, and the timestamp. This is stored in your
browser's local storage, so it persists across sessions.

[Navigate to the "Retrain" tab by clicking "Retrain" in the navigation.
This tab is only visible because we are logged in as admin.]

Now, one of the most powerful features: retraining. This panel is only
visible to admin users. Here I can set the number of epochs and the
batch size, then click "Start Retraining."

[Point to the Epochs field showing "10" and the Batch Size field
showing "32". Do NOT click the button.]

When an admin clicks this button, it sends a request through the API
Gateway to the Airflow REST API, which triggers a DAG called
"retrain_pipeline." That DAG has four sequential tasks: first, it tells
the Data Service to preprocess fresh data. Second, it starts training
on the Training Service, which runs in a background thread so it does
not block the server. Third, it polls the training status every ten
seconds until completion, with a one-hour timeout. And fourth, it
tells the Prediction Service to reload the newly trained model from
disk. The entire cycle is fully automated.

[Navigate back to "Dashboard" tab. Scroll down to the fourth diagram
and click: "4. Monitoring Architecture".]

This brings me to monitoring. This diagram shows how Prometheus, on port
9090, scrapes the /metrics endpoint from four services every fifteen
seconds. We implemented custom Prometheus metrics in every Flask service
using the prometheus_client library. We track request counts, request
latency as histograms, service health, prediction counts per category,
prediction confidence distributions, inference latency, training status,
and training loss and accuracy.

All of this data flows into Grafana through PromQL queries, giving us
the live dashboards you saw embedded in our main interface earlier.

[Click anywhere to close the diagram overlay.]

Now [Speaker B] will cover our security measures, CI/CD pipeline,
and what it takes to maintain this system in production.


