SEGMENT 4 (15:00 - 20:00) | SPEAKER B
"Technology Stack, Security, CI/CD, and Conclusion"
Estimated Words: ~680
================================================================================

[Scroll down to the fifth diagram and click: "5. Technology Stack".]

Thank you, [Speaker A]. Let me start by showing you our complete technology
stack, from the bottom up.

The bottom layer is Infrastructure: Docker Compose orchestrates all
thirteen containers on a bridge network called mlops_network. Prometheus
provides metrics collection. Python 3.11 is our runtime. And every
container has health checks that Docker monitors continuously. If a
service fails, Docker automatically restarts it.

The Orchestration and CI layer includes Apache Airflow for DAG-based
pipeline scheduling, DVC for data version control and reproducibility,
GitHub Actions for continuous integration, and Nginx as our web server
for the UI.

The Data and Storage layer uses pandas and numpy for data manipulation,
DVC for versioning our five point six gigabytes of raw data, SQLite for
the authentication database, and PostgreSQL for Airflow's metadata.

The Application and ML layer is where the core intelligence lives.
TensorFlow and Keras power our LSTM model. NLTK handles natural language
preprocessing. scikit-learn assists with data splitting. And Flask serves
all four microservice APIs.

The top layer, Presentation and UI, includes our custom Web UI, the API
Gateway, plus the Grafana, MLflow, and Airflow user interfaces.

[Click anywhere to close. Navigate to the "Users" tab by clicking
"Users" in the navigation.]

Now let me address security. This User Management panel shows our
role-based access control system. We have two roles: admin and user.
Regular users can only make predictions and view their history. Admins
can retrain models, manage users, and access all system endpoints.

[Point to the users table.]

Authentication uses SHA-256 hashed passwords stored in SQLite. When a
user logs in, the Auth Service generates a cryptographically secure
random token of sixty-four hexadecimal characters. This token must be
sent as a Bearer token in the Authorization header of every API request.
Each new login invalidates the previous token, so stolen tokens become
useless after the legitimate user logs in again.

The API Gateway enforces authentication on every protected route. It
verifies the token with the Auth Service before forwarding any request.
Admin-only endpoints like retraining and user management perform an
additional role check.

For continuous integration, every push to our repository triggers a
GitHub Actions pipeline. It runs flake8 for code linting, pytest for
our test suite that covers data loading, text preprocessing, model
architecture, tokenizer serialization, and authentication logic. It also
checks that no large binary files were accidentally committed. If all
tests pass, it builds Docker images for all five custom services as a
smoke test.

Now, what does it take to maintain this system? There are three key
areas. First, monitoring: Prometheus and Grafana give us real-time
visibility into service health, request latencies, and model performance.
If prediction confidence drops or latency spikes, we know immediately.
Second, retraining: the Airflow DAG allows us to retrain on fresh data
at any time, either manually from the dashboard or on a daily schedule.
Third, reproducibility: DVC tracks our data and pipeline stages, so
any experiment can be reproduced exactly.

[Navigate back to the "Dashboard" tab. Point to the full screen with
all health indicators green.]

To summarize what we have built: a production-grade MLOps system with
thirteen containerized services, an LSTM neural network classifying
products into twenty-seven categories, a complete pipeline from raw
data to real-time predictions, experiment tracking with MLflow,
orchestration with Airflow, performance monitoring with Prometheus
and Grafana, secure role-based authentication, CI/CD with GitHub
Actions, and this single dashboard that brings it all together.

[Pause. Gesture to the screen.]

Everything you see here is live, everything is containerized, and
everything was built from scratch by us.

Thank you for your time. We are happy to take any questions.


